Five creative composition and mood tips to elevate your photography by @aledlewisphotography, an award-winning photographer!   

"I first got into photography on a family holiday in Blackpool. The Blackpool Tower amazed me, and I remember moving around trying to get the right composition, much to my father's annoyance, who was probably worried about how many photos were left in the 35mm!

Since then, I have tried different photography styles, macro, landscape, portraits, etc. Taking as many photos as possible has always been my motto because you might find a diamond out of all of them! As a result, I won the British Photography Awards in the landscape category in 2022, and I think the following principles helped me a lot in developing my artwork: 

1) I make sure that the weather is to my liking. I think of the place I want to photograph and what mood I'd like. Then I travel when the weather suits my desired style. This series is a good example of the atmosphere that attracts me, even when visiting the same spot multiple times. 

2) I like to return to the same spots because conditions change constantly; you'll improve your work by taking images of the same place and seeing the same landscape differently every time. This exercise will allow you to develop an eye and better understand how to frame your subject. 

3) Getting the right composition on a photo can be hard, so I use the rule of thirds as much as possible and take landscape photos in portrait style too. 

4) When taking portrait-style images, I like to (1) align my subject with the horizon or (2) place the horizon in the right-center intersection of the grid while the subject stands on the left-center section. 

5) In these images from the Llyn Padarn Lake, the mountains and lakes' horizon form a natural leading line, creating depth and a three-dimensional effect. By including this compositional element in your images, your viewers will discover more aspects of the photo as you guide their eyes from the foreground to the background and everything in between.”

@aledlewisphotography: We hope this series inspires you to revisit some of your favorite locations in your home country and try these tips! 📸

Nine steps by @aledlewisphotography to edit great landscape photographs! "This series shows some of my favorite images, while the third photo stands out. I always wanted a picture of Tryfan when the light was setting at the end of the day. So, after checking the forecast, I quickly packed my camera bag, hopped in my car, and parked nearby in the Ogwen Valley. Seeing the sun going down quite fast, I rushed up the hill along Afon Lloer, opposite Tryfan, and arrived just as the light disappeared from the mountain's peak.

Tryfan Mountain, with the fading light, was the main focus of the photo, but the stile gave foreground interest, and the stone wall running to the right gave some balance to the image. Then, in post-production, I tried to enhance the key features, keeping the photo as natural as possible. Editing can be a daunting experience for some, but it can be easy, too! 

1) The first step for any photo I edit is adjusting the basics. First, I have always played with the 'Accent' tool, which is magical. 

2) Then, I adjust the exposure, highlights, and shadows. 

3) In the case of the Tryfan mountain image, I found that the temperature was good. 

4) I then went on to darken the sky with a brush, lowering the exposure. 

5) I added contrast and black in certain parts to reveal the clouds' details. 

6) I added 'Texture' to the wall and stile to make them 'pop' as they were in the foreground. Adjustments to saturation and some supercontrast to bring out the highlights in some areas, and a vignette to finish off.

7) The most vital steps of my editing process are the basic adjustments, as in changes to exposure, highlights, and shadows. And 'Accent', of course.

8) The most important lesson I learned in photo editing was experimenting with the different sliders. After downloading to Luminar, I always shift the sliders I want to use to the extreme to see their effect and adjust accordingly. 

9) I also firmly believe in walking away after editing a photo and returning after a few minutes to look at it again. Then, finalize the edit accordingly.” 

@aledlewisphotography: I hope you found these steps helpful! 📸🎨
